entry.title: Precise VsyncRateMin calculation
entry.content:
This change adds a precise calculation of the minimum supported vsync

rate, replacing the value previously accessed from the EDID which is

imprecise due to being encoded as an integer. The precise value is

determined in DisplayMode, and the type is updated accordingly from int

to float where relevant.



In order to support the precise vsync_min calculation, detailed timing

fields are added to DisplayMode which are taken directly from the kernel

mode object. This change is aligned with the goal of improving mode

matching across kernel and userspace (which was not previously possible

when modes had equal resolutions and rates). In future changes,

additional kernel mode fields can be added to DisplayMode as needed.

entry.content:
Per CSS WG resolution, CSS Highlight Pseudo elements should

use the font from their originating element when computing

units for text decorations and the like.



When resolving style, we now check for font relative units in the parent style and recompute style for any highlight that has such units. To avoid memory blow-out, we try to re-use as much as possible of the existing style, only recomputing those with font relative units.



Testing for numerous situations is provided.

entry.title: Animate the two permission modules in Safety Hub
entry.content:
The core of the animation is implemented in the SafetyHubModule class.



However, due to the concept of animations being somewhat incompatible

with the Polymer bindings where DOM elements are reused and rendered

immediately when the underlying model changes, the users of

SafetyHubModule (i.e. UnusedSitePermissionsModule

and NotificationPermissionsModule) must call animation methods at the

right time.



Specifically, they must call "animateShow" on every row immediately

after it is added, and only remove rows in a callback provided to the

"animateHide" method.



Despite not completely trivial, this is a somewhat predictable API that

can be generalized by other implementors of SafetyHubModule subclasses.

entry.title: Multiplanar: Create a shared images per GpuMemoryBuffer
entry.content:
Allow creating multiple shared images for formats which create multiple

GMBs (software or hardware) with multiplanar shared image for software

video decode feature. These are I420 and NV12_DUAL_GMB format cases

where we have multiple GMBs with one for each plane. This allows us to

decouple conversion of client cases where there are multiple GMBs and

hence multiple shared images vs cases where there is a single GMB and

multiple shared images for multiplanar formats, allowing us to launch

feature faster. We can then handle these cases as a follow-up and make

sure there is a single GMB, shared image and mailbox for multiplanar

formats.



Also remove OutputFormat param for method and use stored format and

log when CHECK/DCHECK fail in client SII.



NOTE: This is a non-functional change for now as the feature is only

enabled for Mac which does not use I420/NV12_DUAL_GMB formats.

entry.title: [zlib] Introducing ANZAC++ hash
entry.content:
Since 2015 Chromium's zlib used a hardware accelerated hashing function

(i.e. CRC32) to insert symbols in the dictionary during compression.



As it was suggested by Noel Gordon, turns out that a portable hash can

actually outperform it, yielding an average gain of 30% to 40% faster* compression while keeping similar compression ratios**.



In these days, such gains are equivalent to more than 3 generations

of silicon.



The new hashing function is called ANZAC++ and can be technically

considered a multiplicative hash (i.e. multiply-add-shift-mask).



Aside being faster, it is also portable and doesn't depend on crypto

extensions to perform (i.e. will work on RISC-V and Armv7).



This patch will use ANZAC as default hashing, plus performs a huge cleanup.



* Average gains: m1(31.3%), RPL_e(39.7%), RPL_p(39.4%),

Cascade(39%), ICX(+38%), SPR(41.9%).



** Average compression ratio loss is 0.1% for the snappy data

corpus.

entry.title: Add QueryDisplayConfig Option for VSync Intervals
entry.content:
The way UsePrimaryMonitorVSyncIntervalOnSV3 was originally written was

to utilize Chromium's existing fallback method (previously for when

DwmGetCompositionTimingInfo could be used) which utilized

EnumDisplayConfig which returned DEVMOD.dmDisplayFrequency.

Unfortunately, dmDisplayFrequency is a DWORD & this legacy GDI path

does not support fractional refresh rates.



As a result on displays at frequencies like 29.97hz this could result

in large dropped frame behaviors when playing higher frame rate

content like 60fps, which some sites use as a signal to decrease

quality.



This change uses an alternative API, QueryDisplayConfig, to get

the fractional refresh rate to create a more accurate interval.



(Note: there are still some refresh rates that can enter into this

state where we get large dropped frame rates, e.g. Windows Remote

Desktop may operate at 32hz which does not allow the Video Renderer

Algorithm to set a good cadence. These scenarios are not addressed

by this change & they will also show the same behavior with

DwmGetCompositionTimingInfo)



Bug: 1476048

entry.title: [ios] Refactor Fakebox animation calculations
entry.content:
The code that does these calculations is somewhat hard to understand and

this is an attempt to make it a little easier by introducing an

interpolate method that calculates a value / dimension when given the

starting value, the ending value, and a percent. An example usage would

be to calculate the height of the fakebox given that it is wide at the

start and narrower at the end, and given a percentage of progress

through the animation. Most of the animation is driven by similar

changes to dimensions.



Along the way, a few miscalculations were identified and fixed:

* the top margin of the pinned fakebox was off by one

* the height of the pinned fake toolbar assumed the height of the

separator was 1 pt, when in reality it was one pixel (no matter the

pixel density)
